- Grain and intimacy vs. cinematic lift: The raw, minimally polished sound can feel immediate but it doesn’t deliver the big melodic development and cinematic arrangement I prefer; it leans toward the kind of unvarnished grit I generally appreciate less when I’m selecting an album for studio‑polished, immersive listening.
In short, both discs have strengths (AC/DC aligns with raw guitar energy and cohesive sequencing), but the Elton John CD better fulfills the central, stated priorities—piano focus, orchestration, strong melodic hooks and high‑end studio polish—so it is the clear choice.

